//@ compile-fail
//@ error-contains: unknown type
//@ error-contains: CompletelyMadeUpType

// An unknown type name written *inside a function body* has to be reported.
//
// Checking raises errors through two channels. The checker's own come back from
// `check_all`; resolving a type annotation raises through `Env::error` and lands in
// `env.errors()` instead. The CLI read `env.errors()` only *before* checking — which
// catches a bad annotation on a declaration, since those resolve during `Env::build_with`
// — and afterwards printed only the returned list. Annotations inside bodies resolve
// during checking, so their errors were discarded.
//
// The program then compiled "successfully" with a poison type in it, and the backend's
// guard against an unsubstituted type variable fired, so the user saw an internal compiler
// error rather than the diagnostic the compiler had already produced and thrown away. That
// applied to every unknown type name in a body, not only the one that exposed it.
//
// The corpus harness always read both lists, which is why this file passes here and why
// the two front ends appeared to disagree about which programs were valid.

use std::io;

fn main() {
    let x: CompletelyMadeUpType = 5;
    io::println("this must not compile");
}
